```

### 1.2 Now lets train The Forecast ModelğŸ§®

Now that our dataset is correctly formatted, we can train the
forecasting model. ğŸ‘‰ What the code does: âœ… Loads the prophet package
âœ… Trains the Prophet model using co2_df âœ… Generates a future dataframe
(8 months ahead) for predictions âœ… Prints out future time periods to
confirm structure

```{r}
# Load required libraries
library(zoo)
library(prophet)

# Convert CO2 dataset into a Prophet-compatible format
co2_df <- data.frame(
  ds = zoo::as.yearmon(time(co2)),  # Convert time to Year-Month format
  y = as.numeric(co2)  # Convert values to numeric
)

# Correct column names
colnames(co2_df) <- c("ds", "y")

# Print structure
str(co2_df)

# Print first few rows
head(co2_df)

# Train the Prophet model
m <- prophet(co2_df)

# Create a dataframe for future predictions (8 months ahead)
future <- make_future_dataframe(m, periods = 8, freq = "month")

# Display the first few rows of future dates
head(future)
```

### 1.3 Let's Visualise the Forecast!ğŸ“ˆ

Now that we have been able to train our Prophet model, let's get to
visualizing the predicted CO2 levels! This part will make plots to
enable us to observe the patterns and trends the model is forecasting.âœ¨

```{r}
# Load required libraries
library(zoo)
library(prophet)

# Convert CO2 dataset into a Prophet-compatible format
co2_df <- data.frame(
  ds = zoo::as.yearmon(time(co2)),  # Convert time to Year-Month format
  y = as.numeric(co2)  # Convert values to numeric
)

# Correct column names
colnames(co2_df) <- c("ds", "y")

# Train the Prophet model
model <- prophet(co2_df)

# Create a dataframe for future predictions (8 months ahead)
future <- make_future_dataframe(model, periods = 8, freq = "month")

# Check if future dataframe has data
head(future)

# Generate predictions
forecast <- predict(model, future)

# Check if forecast was generated
head(forecast)

# Plot the forecast
plot(model, forecast)

# Visualise forecast components (trend, seasonality)
prophet_plot_components(model, forecast)

```

### 1.4 Analyse the Forecast! ğŸ“Œ

âœ”ï¸ The cumulative CO2 concentrations are increasing, showing a trend of
increase with time. 

âœ”ï¸ The confidence intervals (yhat_lower and yhat_upper) indicate potential variations in forecasts, i.e., there is some uncertainty in the future predictions of the model.

âœ”ï¸ There can be seasonality, where CO2 can increase and decrease in a periodic manner due to annual trends.

```{r echo=FALSE}
# Summary statistics of the forecast
summary(forecast)

# Extract key forecasted values
tail(forecast[, c("ds", "yhat", "yhat_lower", "yhat_upper")])
```

# The Conclusion ğŸš€

Our journey through COâ‚‚ forecasting with Prophet has been both insightful and eye-opening! By averaging historical COâ‚‚ data dating back to 1959, weâ€™ve successfully built a predictive model that highlights key trends in atmospheric carbon dioxide levels.

**Key Takeaways:**

âœ… Steady Increase in COâ‚‚ Levels
Our forecast reinforces what has been observed for a long time by climate scientistsâ€”COâ‚‚ level is increasing steadily over the years. This is corroborated by real observations from NASA and NOAA, highlighting the gravity of climate observation.

âœ… Seasonal Trends & Annual Variations
Prophet was capable of detecting seasonal variations in COâ‚‚ levels, which could be explained by natural cycles in nature, such as absorption by plants during certain times of the year and increased emissions during winter.


